Message films, i.e., films whose primary, perhaps sole purpose is to teach or otherwise demonstrate some moral, social or ethical lesson, are difficult to execute. They can be so direct, that they border on being documentary, or worse, a CNBC news story. Moreover, they can be preachy even soap boxy--no one appreciates 'being told.' And worse, they can be melodramatic, offering contrived scenes that when executed poorly, scripted poorly, present as cartoons or caricature. The actors in this film are okay and likable, but it's the story that lacks depth, texture, subtext, and subtlety. The characters are one dimensional and bland. The pacing is slow, the editing is virtually nonexistent. The message is universal: behind every face, there is a unique story. This film misses the opportunity to tell the unique story of the characters in this film. Particularly, the white couple that chooses to live in a predominantly black, "urban" neighborhood. What were they thinking? That is an important question to ask, but this film neither asks nor answers that question.
